    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Let's focus on the technical aspects. To test for vacuum leaks in your 2018 Toyota Camry, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Visual Inspection**: Start by visually inspecting all vacuum lines and hoses for cracks, disconnections, or signs of wear. A small leak can be as elusive as a goblin hiding in the shadows.\n\n2. **Smoke Test**: A smoke test involves introducing smoke into the vacuum system. You can either rent a smoke machine or use a smoke bottle with a smoke-generating fluid. With the engine running, the smoke will reveal any leaks as it escapes from the system.\n\n3. **Vacuum Gauge**: If you have a vacuum gauge, you can connect it to the manifold pressure port. With the engine running, a healthy vacuum should be between 17-21 inches of mercury (inHg). If the reading is lower, it indicates a leak.\n\n4. **Listen for Hissing Sounds**: With the engine idling, listen for any hissing sounds that could indicate a vacuum leak. These sounds are like the whispers of goblins trying to sneak by unnoticed.\n\n5. **Check the PCV Valve**: The Positive Crankcase Ventilation",
